<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1437,261,1706]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,312,1343,1369]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[329,625,1344,1369]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicudiscus">
<emphasis box="[329,625,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Pravistylus varicudiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the very long plate with the apical third that is right-angled dorsally. The plate of this species reaches the apex of the pygofer lobe and bears macrosetae (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="54.[151,258,1750,1774]" captionTargetBox="[187,1403,201,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-85@54.[180,1407,197,1753]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURE 1 a–l. Pravistylus species. Pygofer, laterally. a, P. bidentidiscus sp. n.; b, P. brachyphysis sp. n.; c, P. brachyplacus sp. n.; d, P. caenophallus sp. n.; e, P. deltoplacus sp. n.; f–g, P. dentidiscus sp. n.; h, P. digitidiscus sp. n.; i–k, P.eductus(Naudé); l, P. exquadratus (Naudé)." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
aj). Another species with a similar configuration is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[797,966,1419,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitidiscus">
<emphasis box="[797,966,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. digitidiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[984,1079,1418,1444]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="57.[151,255,1711,1735]" captionTargetBox="[198,1389,205,1619]" captionTargetId="figure-63@57.[190,1396,194,1718]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 2 a–i. Pravistylus species. Plate, part or whole structure. a, P. varicudiscus sp. n.; b, P. mecistoplacus sp. n.; c, P. digitidiscus sp. n.; d, P. tanyoplacus sp. n.; e–g, P.eductus(Naudé); h–i, P. exquadratus (Naudé)." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 2 c</figureCitation>
), but with the plate distinctly shorter, usually without macrosetae, only a short section of the apex is curved or bent dorsally, or sometimes it is right-angled (
<figureCitation box="[337,431,1493,1519]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="54.[151,258,1750,1774]" captionTargetBox="[187,1403,201,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-85@54.[180,1407,197,1753]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURE 1 a–l. Pravistylus species. Pygofer, laterally. a, P. bidentidiscus sp. n.; b, P. brachyphysis sp. n.; c, P. brachyplacus sp. n.; d, P. caenophallus sp. n.; e, P. deltoplacus sp. n.; f–g, P. dentidiscus sp. n.; h, P. digitidiscus sp. n.; i–k, P.eductus(Naudé); l, P. exquadratus (Naudé)." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 1 h</figureCitation>
). In undissected specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[789,953,1493,1518]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitidiscus">
<emphasis box="[789,953,1493,1518]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. digitidiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the apex of the plate is inserted ventrally between margins of the pygofer lobe. The female sternite 7 of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[974,1171,1531,1556]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicudiscus">
<emphasis box="[974,1171,1531,1556]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. varicudiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristically longitudinally rectangular, with a short triangular ligula (
<figureCitation box="[818,888,1568,1594]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="70.[151,255,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[228,1356,197,1819]" captionTargetId="figure-105@70.[225,1359,194,1900]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURE 7 a–af. Pravistylus species. Sternite 7 of female, whole structure, or posterior margin. a–b, P. bidentidiscus sp. n.; c, P. brachyphysis sp. n.; d, P. brachyplacus sp. n.; e–f, P. caenophallus sp. n.; g–i, P. deltoplacus sp. n.; j–l, P. dentidiscus sp. n.; m–n, P. digitidiscus sp. n.; o–t, P. eductus (Naudé); u–w, P. exquadratus (Naudé); x–aa, P. indistinctidiscus sp. n.; ab–af, P. interdiscus sp. n." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
cf), whereas in all other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1975" box="[1304,1436,1568,1593]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1436,1568,1593]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Pravistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the sternite is usually transversely rectangular with a long ligula, or sometimes square. There is a striking similarity in the plate of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[438,614,1643,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicudiscus">
<emphasis box="[438,614,1643,1668]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">P. varicudiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1975" box="[869,966,1643,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Vilargus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,966,1643,1668]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Vilargus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although the aedeagus and sternite 7 of the female of these two species differs markedly.
</paragraph>
